   {:e #blake3 "2e50405565458c5b704cddff1b9e66917d4f6eaab8c49d76e18b3ad5e653f902" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1773892875 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2e50405565458c5b704cddff1b9e66917d4f6eaab8c49d76e18b3ad5e653f902" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-264d5260; Session entity: :task/t-2961e2a9; Session entity: :task/t-a73abfb0; Session entity: :task/t-f66ec5af; FIRST PRINCIPLES ANALYSIS of the 'phantom decision' failure mode. The fundamental problem: DECISIONS and TASKS are different entity types that SHOULD be linked but AREN'T. When I observe 'DESIGN DECISION: implement X with approach Y', that creates an :observation/* entity. When I create a task 'implement X', that creates a :task/* entity. But there is NO automatic link between them. The decision references work that should become a task, but the system doesn't detect this. THREE-LAYER GUARD analysis: (1) PREVENTION (structural): Currently NOTHING prevents decisions from being orphaned — the data model doesn't enforce decision-to-task linkage. (2) DETECTION (observational): Currently NO mechanism detects orphaned decisions at harvest time. The harvest pipeline looks for harvestable knowledge but doesn't check whether decisions have corresponding tasks. (3) CORRECTION (adaptive): Currently NO learning loop — the system doesn't track decision-to-task linkage rate or improve it over time. ALL THREE LAYERS ARE MISSING. This is why the failure mode recurred across TWO sessions.; Session entity: :task/t-df3adca0; DEEPER ANALYSIS: Why does this failure mode exist in the first place? The agent's ATTENTION BUDGET is finite (k*). During a design session, the agent is in HIGH-DOF exploration mode — discovering structure, making decisions, designing systems. Task creation is LOW-DOF execution — mechanical, repetitive, requires switching cognitive mode. The mode switch costs k*. After making 10 design decisions, the agent's remaining k* is low, and switching to 'now create 10 tasks' feels like a downgrade. The agent DEFERS task creation ('I will create these tasks later') and then the conversation ends before 'later' arrives. This is the BASIN COMPETITION model from ADR-GUIDANCE-002: exploration (Basin A) and task creation (Basin B) compete for the same attention budget. The agent stays in Basin A because it's more productive there, and task creation never happens. THE STRUCTURAL FIX is not 'remember to create tasks' (process obligation, decays under pressure). The fix is to make task creation a SIDE EFFECT of the design decision, not a separate action. When braid observe captures a design decision, the system should auto-detect actionable content and SUGGEST (or auto-create) the corresponding task. The decision and the task are created in ONE cognitive action, not two.; SOLUTION DESIGN: Decision-Task Integrity Constraint (DTIC). FORMAL MODEL: Let D be the set of decisions in the store (entities with :intent/decision attribute). Let T be the set of tasks. A decision d is ACTIONABLE if it references implementation work (contains verbs like 'implement', 'add', 'create', 'fix', 'wire', 'build'). An actionable decision d is TRACKED if there exists a task t such that t traces to d or d references t. The INTEGRITY CONSTRAINT: every actionable decision must be tracked. DETECTION: At harvest time, scan all decisions since last harvest. For each actionable decision, check whether a corresponding task exists. If not, emit a HARVEST WARNING (not an error — the agent may have intentionally deferred). The warning is SPECIFIC: 'Decision D-xxx references implementation work but no task exists. Crystallize: braid task create <suggested-title> --relates-to <decision-entity>'. FROM API-AS-PROMPT: The warning IS a prompt that includes a ready-to-use command. The agent can copy-paste it to create the missing task. This is the DEMONSTRATION principle applied to error recovery. PREVENTION (structural, longer-term): braid observe with --category design-decision could auto-prompt: 'This decision references implementation. Create a task? [Y/n] braid task create <suggested-title>'. This makes the happy path go through task creation — making the orphaned-decision state harder to reach.; Session entity: :task/t-8ac8f2cc; COMPLETENESS CHECK: Cross-referencing ALL design decisions from this session against task set. (1) Coupling-Coherence Isomorphism -> covered by TOPO-DENSITY (t-3f8df462). (2) Five coupling dimensions with staged weights -> covered by TOPO-COMPOSITE (t-b7d04e92). (3) Agent lifecycle = harvest/seed -> covered by EPIC Agent Lifecycle. (4) F(T) 7-dimensional fitness -> covered by FT-COMPUTE (t-072d762f). (5) R(t) two-level routing -> covered by TOPO-ROUTING (t-bccdf2b3). (6) Spectral entropy thresholds -> covered by TOPO-SPECTRAL (t-21af64fc). (7) Pyramid summaries -> covered by PYRAMID-DISPLAY (t-17edf3df) + PYRAMID-TOPO (t-ad704639). (8) Data-model-as-prompt -> covered by t-1029e16f. (9) Decision-Task Integrity -> covered by DTIC EPIC (4 tasks). (10) Self-bootstrap via TOPO-QUICK -> covered by 9 QUICK subtasks. (11) Task search/filter -> covered by t-dbca7795, t-ea2d7a05. (12) Error recovery -> covered by t-8b308e91 + TOPO-ERROR (t-463e815d). (13) Plan persistence as datoms -> covered by TOPO-PERSIST (t-dc54f525). (14) Agent naming -> covered by t-278ebb33 + QUICK-1 (t-254ca64d). (15) Unused Op import -> covered by t-8e558ef9. (16) lib.rs re-exports -> covered by t-b89e76b8. (17) Task-set integration tests -> covered by t-282227bb. (18) Spec dependency edges -> covered by t-c2bbcda9. ASSESSMENT: ALL 18 design decisions are covered by at least one task. Zero orphaned decisions. The DTIC system, had it existed, would have found zero gaps in this final state.; Session entity: :task/t-254ca64d; Session entity: :task/t-8d9df01d; Session entity: :task/t-ca4e98bd; Session entity: :task/t-32f47d25; Session entity: :task/t-5b3ea264; FAILURE MODE ANALYSIS: Decisions made in conversation but never tracked in any system. This happened TWICE — Session 025 designed 10 topology tasks that were never transacted; Session 026 had to recreate them from conversation context summary. Root cause: the CONVERSATION is ephemeral but DECISIONS are durable. The harvest/seed lifecycle (SEED.md S5) was designed to solve exactly this — extract durable knowledge from ephemeral conversations. But harvest captures OBSERVATIONS and DECISIONS, not TASKS. When an agent says 'we should implement X' during a conversation, that decision lives ONLY in the conversation context. If the agent forgets to run braid task create before the conversation ends, the task is LOST. This is EPISTEMIC DIVERGENCE (reconciliation taxonomy type 1): the gap between what the agent knows (the decision exists) and what the store knows (no task entity). The harvest process should detect this gap — decisions that reference implementation work but have no corresponding task entity.; Session entity: :task/t-efb42dc7; THINKING: What is the single most accretive addition? The topology compilation pipeline is 37 tasks across 7 batches — weeks of work. But the FIRST USER of braid topology plan is... US. We have 37 tasks to parallelize RIGHT NOW. This is a BOOTSTRAP PROBLEM: the system that would optimize our work doesn't exist yet, and building it IS the work. But we ALREADY HAVE: ready_task_files(), compute_file_coupling(), partition_by_file_coupling(), compute_routing_from_store(). The basic partition is ONE function call away from being a CLI command. What if we wire what EXISTS into a minimal viable braid topology plan --quick that uses ONLY file coupling + connected components? Then EXTEND IT: the plan output emits per-agent SEED PROMPTS — optimized prompt configurations that establish deep formal basins for each agent's partition. This is API-as-prompt applied recursively: the topology plan OUTPUT is itself a prompt, structured using everything we know about prompt optimization (demonstrations over constraints, spec-language, k*-aware compression, trajectory seeding).; SESSION 026 FINAL PLANNING AUDIT. 38 new tasks created across 5 EPICs. ALL tasks verified to have :task/background AND :task/acceptance datoms. Zero dependency cycles. Dependency DAG is acyclic. Store integrity: 18,104 datoms, 2,395 entities, 1,817 txns. Key decisions recorded as observations: Coupling-Coherence Isomorphism, Five-phase topology plan, Agent lifecycle as harvest/seed, F(T) measurement architecture, R(t) two-level routing, Spectral entropy thresholds, Prompt surface hierarchy, Data-model-as-prompt, Pyramid summaries, Decision-Task Integrity Constraint, Self-bootstrap via TOPO-QUICK. Three critical codebase compatibility fixes applied: von_neumann_entropy signature (trilateral takes &Store, topology needs eigenvalue-based), fiedler signature (graph.rs takes &DiGraph, topology needs Laplacian from DenseMatrix), KernelError needs Topology variant. READY TO EXECUTE: Batch 0 has 9 tasks with zero dependencies covering: Op import fix, schema registration, spec dep edges, topology events, pyramid display, task search, task filtering, task-set tests, title shortening. Then TOPO-QUICK (9 subtasks, ~3.5h) self-bootstraps the system.; SOLUTION ARCHITECTURE: Three mechanisms at three time scales. (1) IMMEDIATE (during observe): When braid observe text contains actionable verbs (implement, add, create, fix, wire, build, refactor, test) AND references a system component (file path, spec ID, module name), append a SUGGESTION to the guidance footer: 'Actionable decision detected. Crystallize: braid task create <auto-title> --relates-to <obs-entity>'. The auto-title is extracted from the observation using the same NLP that extract_task_files uses for file paths. This is the PREVENTION layer — the prompt nudges the agent to create the task in the same cognitive flow. (2) HARVEST-TIME (end of session): harvest_pipeline already scans for harvestable knowledge. Add a new harvest check: for each observation with :intent/decision category or actionable verb content, query for tasks that reference the observation entity OR tasks with similar title text. If no match, include in harvest report as 'UNTRACKED DECISIONS: N decisions reference implementation work with no corresponding task'. This is the DETECTION layer. (3) SEED-TIME (start of next session): When braid seed assembles context for the next session, include untracked decisions PROMINENTLY in the Next Actions section: 'From prior session: 3 design decisions without tasks. Crystallize first: (1) braid task create ... (2) braid task create ...' This carries the orphaned decisions ACROSS sessions — the next agent sees them immediately. This is the CORRECTION layer — the system LEARNS about untracked decisions and surfaces them proactively.; Session entity: :task/t-8bf090e7\nSession entity: :task/t-1919718e; Session entity: :task/t-177a5248" :op :assert}
